{
  "$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/claude-code-settings.json"
}

/*
SETTINGS.JSON - Project Configuration
=====================================

Location: .claude/settings.json
Purpose: Team-shared configuration (permissions, env vars, hooks, model defaults)
Commit: YES - This is shared with the entire team

IMPORTANT: This file configures what Claude Code can do in this project.
Review permissions carefully for security.

CONFIGURATION SECTIONS
======================

1. PERMISSIONS (REQUIRED)
-------------------------
Control what tools and commands Claude can use.

permissions: {
  "allow": [...],  // Auto-approved without asking
  "ask": [...],    // Prompt for confirmation each time
  "deny": [...]    // Explicitly blocked
}

HOW TO CONFIGURE ALLOW LIST:
- What commands do developers run frequently?
- What is safe to run without review?
- What read operations are low-risk?

Common patterns to allow:
- Git status/read operations: "Bash(git status)", "Bash(git log *)", "Bash(git diff *)"
- Build commands: "Bash(npm run build)", "Bash(make)", "Bash(cargo build)"
- Test commands: "Bash(npm test)", "Bash(pytest)", "Bash(cargo test)"
- Lint commands: "Bash(npm run lint)", "Bash(flake8)", "Bash(cargo clippy)"

HOW TO CONFIGURE DENY LIST:
- What files contain secrets?
- What operations are dangerous?
- What should never be accessed?

Common patterns to deny:
- Credential files: "Read(./.env)", "Read(./.env.*)", "Read(./secrets/**)"
- Config with API keys: "Read(./config/credentials.json)"
- Destructive commands: "Bash(rm -rf /)", "Bash(dd *)"

HOW TO CONFIGURE ASK LIST:
- What has side effects?
- What should be reviewed before running?
- What might be destructive?

Common patterns to ask:
- Git push: "Bash(git push *)"
- File deletion: "Bash(rm *)", "Bash(rmdir *)"
- Network requests: "WebFetch", "Bash(curl *)"
- Database modifications: "Bash(psql *)"

PATTERN SYNTAX:
- "Tool" - All uses of that tool
- "Tool(pattern)" - Specific pattern match
- "Tool(pattern *)" - Prefix match
- "*" wildcard matches any characters
- Read/Edit paths can use relative paths

EXAMPLES:
"Bash" - All bash commands
"Bash(git *)" - All git commands
"Bash(npm run *)" - All npm run commands
"Read(./src/**)" - All files in src directory
"Read(./.env)" - Specific file

2. ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES (OPTIONAL)
-----------------------------------
Set environment variables for every Claude session.

env: {
  "VAR_NAME": "value",
  "ANOTHER_VAR": "value"
}

Use for:
- Setting NODE_ENV
- Setting PYTHONPATH
- Project-specific variables
- Non-sensitive configuration

NEVER put secrets here - use settings.local.json for personal env vars.

3. MODEL DEFAULT (OPTIONAL)
---------------------------
Set the default model for this project.

model: "claude-sonnet-4-6"

Available models depend on your Claude Code version and account.
Common options: claude-sonnet-4-6, claude-opus-4-6

4. HOOKS (OPTIONAL)
-------------------
Automate workflows by running commands at lifecycle events.

hooks: {
  "preToolUse": [...],
  "postToolUse": [...],
  "onStart": [...]
}

Use for:
- Running lint before commit
- Sending notifications
- Updating status

5. OTHER SETTINGS (OPTIONAL)
----------------------------
- effortLevel: "low" | "medium" | "high"
- defaultMode: Permission mode default
- sandbox: Sandboxing configuration
- outputStyle: Default output style

See full schema: https://json.schemastore.org/claude-code-settings.json

DISCOVERY PROCESS
=================

To configure for your project:

1. BUILD/TEST COMMANDS:
   - Check package.json "scripts"
   - Check Makefile
   - Check build configuration files
   - Check CI/CD config
   - Ask: What commands run daily?

2. SECURITY ANALYSIS:
   - List files that contain secrets (.env, credentials)
   - Identify sensitive directories
   - Consider what should never be auto-approved
   - Think about destructive operations

3. WORKFLOW ANALYSIS:
   - What git operations are common?
   - What file operations happen regularly?
   - What network calls might be needed?

EXAMPLE CONFIGURATIONS
======================

Node.js Project:
{
  "permissions": {
    "allow": [
      "Bash(git status)",
      "Bash(git log *)",
      "Bash(git diff *)",
      "Bash(npm run *)",
      "Bash(npm test)",
      "Read(~/.npmrc)"
    ],
    "deny": [
      "Read(./.env)",
      "Read(./.env.*)",
      "Read(./secrets/**)"
    ],
    "ask": [
      "Bash(git push *)",
      "Bash(npm publish *)"
    ]
  },
  "env": {
    "NODE_ENV": "development"
  }
}

Python Project:
{
  "permissions": {
    "allow": [
      "Bash(git status)",
      "Bash(git log *)",
      "Bash(python -m pytest *)",
      "Bash(pip install *)",
      "Read(~/.zshrc)"
    ],
    "deny": [
      "Read(./.env)",
      "Read(./instance/**)"
    ],
    "ask": [
      "Bash(git push *)",
      "Bash(pip uninstall *)"
    ]
  },
  "env": {
    "PYTHONPATH": "./src"
  }
}

Rust Project:
{
  "permissions": {
    "allow": [
      "Bash(git status)",
      "Bash(cargo build)",
      "Bash(cargo test)",
      "Bash(cargo clippy)",
      "Bash(cargo check)"
    ],
    "deny": [
      "Read(./.env)",
      "Read(./secrets/**)"
    ],
    "ask": [
      "Bash(git push *)",
      "Bash(cargo publish *)"
    ]
  }
}

SECURITY BEST PRACTICES
=======================

1. Start restrictive, then relax
2. Review what you're allowing
3. Deny access to secrets
4. Ask before destructive operations
5. Pre-approve only safe, read-only operations
6. Consider file permissions (don't allow reading ~/.ssh/*)
7. Be careful with wildcards - "Bash(*)" allows ANY command

SCHEMA REFERENCE
================

Always include the $schema line for IDE autocomplete:
"$schema": "https://json.schemastore.org/claude-code-settings.json"

This enables validation and autocomplete in VS Code, Cursor, etc.
*/
